{{Expand German|Uranylperoxid|date=July 2014}} {{chembox | verifiedrevid = 403121071 | Name = Uranyl peroxide | ImageFile = <!-- | ImageSize = 200px --> | ImageName = Uranyl peroxide | OtherNames = | Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers | CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}} | CASNo = }} | Section2 = {{Chembox Properties | Formula = UO<sub>4</sub>&middot;nH<sub>2</sub>O | MolarMass = 302.03 g/mol (as UO<sub>4</sub>) | Density = | Solvent = | SolubleOther = | MeltingPt = | BoilingPt =}} }} '''[[Uranyl]] peroxide''' or '''uranium peroxide''' hydrate (UO<sub>4</sub>·nH<sub>2</sub>O) is a pale-yellow, soluble [[peroxide]] of [[uranium]]. It is found to be present at one stage of the [[enriched uranium]] fuel cycle and in [[yellowcake]] prepared via the ''in situ'' leaching and resin [[ion exchange]] system. This compound, also expressed as: UO<sub>3</sub>·(H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>)·(H<sub>2</sub>O), is very similar to [[uranium trioxide]] hydrate UO<sub>3</sub>·nH<sub>2</sub>O. The dissolution behaviour of both compounds are very sensitive to the hydration state (n can vary between 0 and 4). One main characteristic of uranium peroxide is that it consists of small needles with an average AMAD of about 1.1&nbsp;µm.
The uranyl minerals [[studtite]], UO<sub>4</sub>·4H<sub>2</sub>O, and metastudtite, UO<sub>4</sub>·2H<sub>2</sub>O, are the only minerals discovered to date found to contain peroxide.
